'''''Happy Trails''''' is a video game programmed by [[Carol Shaw]] for the [[Intellivision]] console and released by [[Activision]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.intellivisionlives.com/bluesky/games/credits/activision.shtml#happytrails | title=Activision Games For Intellivision | accessdate=August 28, 2016 | archive-date=December 25, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225120034/http://www.intellivisionlives.com/bluesky/games/credits/activision.shtml#happytrails | url-status=dead }}</ref> The player must navigate a character through a broken maze to collect gold.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19630520&id=Hv8uAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TNwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2470,3525667&hl=en | title=Video Action: Company Shook Industry with Early Ideas | work=Kentucky New Era | date=May 27, 1983 | accessdate=September 5, 2016 | author=Bentley, Rick}}</ref> Shaw previously wrote ''[[River Raid]]'' for the Atari 2600.<ref name=giantlist/>

''Happy Trails'' is a clone of the 1982 [[Konami]] arcade game ''[[Loco-Motion (video game)|Loco-Motion]]''.<ref name=locolives>{{cite web |title=Loco-Motion |url=http://www.intellivisionlives.com/bluesky/games/credits/1983b.html#locomotion |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611110356/http://www.intellivisionlives.com/bluesky/games/credits/1983b.html#locomotion |url-status=dead |archive-date=2018-06-11 |website=IntellvisionLives.com}}</ref> Mattel was working on an official port, but ''Happy Trails'' was published first, resulting in ''Loco-Motion'' being sold at a discount and without any marketing support.<ref name=locolives/>

==Reception==
''Joystik'' magazine wrote, "This is a great game. The strategic possibilities are seemingly endless," giving an overall rating of 5 out of 5 stars.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Home Front: Happy Trails |journal=Joystik |date=September 1983 |volume=2 |issue=1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/joystik_magazine-1983-09/page/n54 53] |url=https://archive.org/details/joystik_magazine-1983-09}}</ref>

